Two men have been arrested in Bungoma for allegedly killing a brother over a Sh50 debt. Nickson Matumbai, 61, was allegedly bludgeoned and slashed to death with a panga on Saturday. His body was dumped in the bushes. Police arrested his 33-year-old brother and 50-year-old cousin. The killing took place at Temba village, Misikhu location in Webuye East constituency. Matumbai is believed to have been killed with blunt objects and a panga, all recovered by police. Earlier, the suspects are believed to have been drinking in a changáa den. Neighbours said Matumbai and his younger brother had earlier quarrelled over the Sh50 debt. Assistant county commissioner Charles Banda confirmed the murder, saying the two suspects were cooperating. Banda urged family members with disputes not to take the law into their own hands. "If you are having any differences with family members that has created disagreement, don't go to an extent of taking the life of your own brother or sister," Banda said. "Instead, come to us for action to be taken." The victim bore deep cuts to had deep cuts on the lower chin and forehead. Police recovered a blood-stained panga and blunt objects. Matumbai's son Michael Wafula described his father's death as a big blow to the family as the deceased was the family's sole breadwinner. “May those who killed my father find no peace in their life. Father,  follow them to the bitter end,” he said. He appealed to police to investigate with haste. He said his father was a hardworking, focused person and his death has shocked the village. Wafula said the family was alerted by noise from residents who had visited crime scene. "We were at home. We did not know what had happened, though our father had not returned home after his daily activities," he said. He said his father's body bore injuries to the face and head, shoulders and hands. Neighbours said there's a lot of chang'aa brewing in the area and asked police to end it. (Edited by V. Graham)